                    <section>
                        <h2>Overview</h2>
                        <p>Public International Law is the set of rules, principles, and standards of conduct that are considered binding on states and other international actors in their mutual relations. It governs issues like state sovereignty, human rights, international trade, and the laws of war.</p>
                    </section>

                    <hr>

                    <section>
                        <h2>Key Concepts & Sources</h2>
                        <ul class="list-group list-group-flush">
                            <li class="list-group-item"><strong>State Sovereignty</strong> â€“ The principle that states are supreme and independent within their own territory.</li>
                            <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Treaties</strong> â€“ Legally binding agreements between states (Art. 38(1)(a) of ICJ Statute).</li>
                            <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Customary International Law</strong> â€“ General and consistent practice of states followed by a sense of legal obligation (opinio juris).</li>
                            <li class="list-group-item"><strong>General Principles of Law</strong> â€“ Principles common to the major legal systems worldwide.</li>
                            <li class="list-group-item"><strong>Judicial Decisions & Teachings</strong> â€“ Subsidiary means for the determination of rules of law.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </section>
                    
                    <hr>

